Layout of a for loop
for (var in seq) {<- start of loop
# body of loop
}<- end of loop
var is a counter variable (value of var increments by 1 each time you run the loop)
seq specifies start and end values
var i,j,k (i.e. up to triple loop)
x = 1:1000
for (i in seq_along(x)) { ##fastest way for large loops
##
}

#simple example of for loop
myDat <- round(runif(10), digits=2)
for (i in seq_along(myDat)) {
  cat("loop number = ",i,
      "vector element = ",myDat[i], "\n")
}

###########################################################################################
# FUNCTION: RanWalk
# stochastic random walk (model population growth)
# Input: times = number of time steps
#          n1 = initial population size
#          lambda = finite rate of increase
#          noiseSD = sd of normal distribution
#          with mean = 0 (add or remove a random number of individuals)
# Output: vector n with population sizes > 0
#         until extinction of population occurs (NA)
# _________________________________________________________________________________________

library(tcltk)
RanWalk <- function(times=100, 
                    n1=50,
                    lambda=1.001, 
                    noiseSD=10) {
  n <- rep(NA, times)
  n[1] <- n1
  noise <- rnorm(n=times, mean=0, sd=noiseSD)

for (i in 1:(times-1)) {
  n[i + 1] <- lambda*n[i] + noise[i] #would write in a manusript as n(t+1) = lambda(nt) + e
if(n[i + 1] <= 0){
  n[i+ 1] <- NA
  cat("Population extinction at time", 
      i-1, "\n")
  tkbell()
  break} #end of conditional statement
  } #end of for loop
return(n)
} #end of function
head(RanWalk())
## [1] 50.00000 42.61759 27.59474 33.74560 24.70486 31.00531
plot(RanWalk(), type="o")

plot(RanWalk(lambda = 1.05, noiseSD=0), type="o") #turn stochastic noise off

plot(RanWalk(lambda = 0.98, noiseSD=0), type="o")

plot(RanWalk(lambda = 0.98, noiseSD=5), type="o")
## Population extinction at time 16

plot(RanWalk(lambda = 1, noiseSD=5), type="o")

##################################################################################################
# FUNCTION: SpeciesAreaCurve
# power function for species richness and areas
# Input: A is a vector of island areas; c is the intercept concept; z is the slope constant
# Output: S a vector of predicted species richness
# ________________________________________________________________________________________________
SpeciesAreaCurve <- function(A=1:5000, c=0.5, z=0.26) {
  S <- c*(A^z)
return(S)
}
head(SpeciesAreaCurve())
## [1] 0.5000000 0.5987394 0.6653061 0.7169776 0.7598051 0.7966899
##################################################################################################
# FUNCTION: SpeciesAreaPlot
# plot the species area curve
# Input: A=vector of island areas; c = single parameter for constant; z= single parameter for slope
# Output: smoothed graph witha paramters shown
# ________________________________________________________________________________________________
SpeciesAreaPlot <- function(A=1:5000, 
                            c=0.5, 
                            z=0.26) {
  plot(x=A, y=SpeciesAreaCurve(A,c,z), 
       type="l", xlab="Island Area", 
       ylab="S", ylim=c(0,1000))
  mtext(paste("c = ", c,"z=", z), cex=0.7)
return()
}
SpeciesAreaPlot()

#now sweep and build a grid of plots!
#global variables
cPars <- c(100, 150,175)
zPars <- c(0.10, 0.16, 0.26, 0.3)
par(mfrow=c(3,4))

for (i in seq_along(cPars)) {
  for (j in seq_along(zPars)) {
    SpeciesAreaPlot(c=cPars[i], z=zPars[j])
  }
}

#looping with for
#cutPoint <- 0.1
cutPoint <- 0.0001
z <- NA
ranData <- runif(100)
for(i in seq_along(ranData)){
  z <- ranData[i]
  if(z < cutPoint) break
}
print(z)
## [1] 0.7738443
#looping with while
z <- NA
cycleNumber <- 0
while (is.na(z) |  z >= cutPoint) {
  z <- runif(1)
  cycleNumber <- cycleNumber + 1
}
print(z)
## [1] 2.00842e-05
print(cycleNumber)
## [1] 9663
#looping with repeat
z <- NA
cycleNumber <- 0 
repeat {
  z <- runif(1)
  cycleNumber <- cycleNumber + 1
  if (z <= cutPoint) break
}
print(z)
## [1] 1.649535e-05
print(cycleNumber)
## [1] 3622
